3d5d8ba108-11-15 3d5d8ba1Father's Day Donner Summit Traditional3d5d8ba1 3d5d8ba12 months, 57 tries. Poor Style: I TR'd it for 2 weeks with a mini traxion because I had no partner. I used every single bolt to work the route initially, at least one bolt during every lead attempt except the send, and several bolts to clean the gear after every lead. I used tape on the back of my right hand. I made my first 5.10 rubber knee pad and used it proficiently. AND, when I sent, I skipped every single bolt while placing all gear on lead. Mantled without clipping the anchors, untied, and soloed off the ledge. Very special journey on a super line. Bottom Half: OTCU, .5C, .75C, G Alien. Nest: .3C, G/Y Alien Hybrid, #1C. Top Half: YTCU, BTCU, #4 BD Nut, #5 WC Nut. 40+ footers on gear - SO FUN! ***3d5d8ba1

b3c1c77c14-11-10 b3c1c77cAll Under Heaven New River Gorge / Cotton Top FA, Traditionalb3c1c77c b3c1c77cThis sick dihedral grabbed my eye as the best Line on the cliff. Unbelievable that it remained undone for so long. Find it between Love Sock and Tainted Love. It starts very wide with stemming on the outside and then becomes a left facing Purple TCU splitter with pods. Left wall is vertical and right wall is overhung. Crux is a 6ft boulder problem at 30ft where no pods exist. Above it gets steep and juggy to a big horn and calf hang off it at the roof's lip. An ultra funky get in the V-Slot move guards the exit to vertical terrain. Breakdown is 10+, V5/6, 11a with most of the 12ft total overhang coming from the 11a bit. May be easier for girls with small fingers. PTCU, PTCU, .5C4, .3C4, BTCU, crux, #1C4, STCU, #2C4, YTCU. Simply amazing climb. ***b3c1c77c

Supreme route. FA in '83. ***e193f045

4001920b14-12-18 4001920bLinear Encounters New River Gorge / Endless Traditional4001920b 4001920b5 pieces. Wow! Only in the realm of world class super splitters do you have Linear Encounters. Clean ring locks lead strait away from the ground and an awkward move out of a V-Slot into a left facing dihedral guards the opening. Rings and super tight hands persist through the dihedral to a rooflet and changing corners move. Few feet, use the crack. Stand up to a small roof and traverse a few moves of fingers to the lip where a perfect extended hands pod waits. No good feet make for a couple real moves to stand up. The now perfect face crack tapers then ends. Tenuous face moves pass the fixed bashy on the final vertical headwall adding spice and a greater sense of achievement. Brilliance from bottom to top. Did not clip bashy, put in purple tcu just left of it. Plucked by Mike Artz and Andrew Barry in '85. Lucky lads. ***4001920b

d584bf6814-12-18 d584bf68Crack a Smile New River Gorge / Endless Traditionald584bf68 d584bf684 pieces. Magnificent line! Real world crack skills required to enjoy this wide splitter. A short overhung dihedral tapers to a face splitter just above head height. The opening move starts with a hand stack at the lip and a crux is encountered immediately getting out of both the dihedral and the hand stack. Stand up to a small barnical covered hands roof. Above it, crawl in as the growing OW enters a gently left leaning left facing dihedral. A few hand jams and small face holds do exist and some small gear also negates the use of monster cams. The crack constricts to a hands pod then goes OW again. Soon the entire right leg has been swallowed and you can see through to the other side of the flake. Break out the skills and you will be back to fists by the top. Stepped left to Raging Waters anchor. Slow and easy climbing. Crawl in! FA in '86. ***d584bf68

2f9bf0f13-11-24 2f9bf0fUnknown New River Gorge / Orange Oswald Traditional2f9bf0f 2f9bf0f3 pieces. .4C, #1C, #2C. Splitter just right of Barfing Butterflies. OK, So This One Blew Me Away. Twice. When I showed up, I walked the cliff to see what I wanted to do, climbed for the day and then looked at the guide when the day was done. This is the best line on the cliff. Period. Of everything here, this was the one I would not leave without. It starts with some easy horizontal ledge stuff to 10ft and then you roll right into the ultimate, so splitter finger crack with face features and orange rock. It grows in size and about halfway up the route you hit a small roof with kneebars. Tight hands here. Pulling the roof gains the crown jewel 60 degree V-slot of gold stone capped with a small roof. Yes, the splitter strait out the center is absolutely perfect hands. The easy exit is actually a jug rail out the right side. Water worn, rounded face holds surround the still perfect splitter until it touches the anchors at #3 camalot size. Wow! So Good. Definately Blown Away. When I looked at the guide after the day was done, I expected to find a really good name attached to this one. Alas, some how no name credit was given. I was blown away for the second time. I would offer to name it "God's Own Stone" but that one is already taken. ***2f9bf0f

5b99e16909-08-14 5b99e169Palisade Traverse Palisade Range, CA Traditional5b99e169 5b99e169Free solo, Grade VI. This is the 8.5 mile long, unbroken ridge that makes up almost the entire Palisade Range in the High Sierra. Averaging an altitude close to 14,000 ft for the entire length, it is the highest continuous ridge in the lower 48 states. We guess there to be somewhere between 70,000 and 80,000 ft of rock climbing. 37.5 hrs bivy to Agassiz, 40.75 hrs bivy to car. Left the bivy at 3:15 am on 8-13-09 and topped Agassiz at 4:45 on 8-14-09. Traded a rope, rack, swami belt, and belay devise, for a down coat and sleeping bag between two people, and two space blankets. Still no sleep due to ripping 32 degree winds that started at dark and lasted through the morning. 20 summit registers above 13,000 ft and 6 above 14,000 ft. Potentially the hardest route I will ever send. ***5b99e169

c0b451ba15-05-05 c0b451baBig Chimney Gunks Traditionalc0b451ba c0b451baFree solo. Two L facing chimneys on this one. The first is shorter and much easier. It hits a roof and a squeeze horizontal leading right to the second chimney. The horizontal fit he upper half of my torso and my left leg in an awkward "Harding Slot" style shuffle. Interesting for sure. The guide mentions that the second chimney is "loose and filled with pigeon poop." Dead Wrong. Perfectly clean smooth rock awaits with just enough small foot jibs to make it all work. Fairly serious and no pro whatsoever. A little rough on my bair knees. At the top is a good belay ledge and face jugs that run to the finish. One of the older routes. FA in '42. ***c0b451ba

3a8df6eb12-03-30 3a8df6ebPilar Harper's Ferry, WV / Hwy 340 near VA state line Traditional3a8df6eb 3a8df6ebP1 5.1 35ft, P2 5.0 25ft. Free solo. Park on the north side of Hwy 340 at south east junction of the Shenandoah and Potomic Rivers. There are 3 old bridge pillars crossing the Shenandoah River at that junction that form a perfect line pointing to this pillar about 80 yds above the road. P1 starts on the NE side of the pillar in a broken dihedral. Probably never been climbed. Spits you out on a big ledge on the south east side of the pillar and at the base of the final pitch. A manditory 5.0 move around the right side of the small roof will take you to the top. I can imagine P2 to the top to have been done as far back as the confederates and would not claim FA, but FA is possible. *3a8df6eb
